<br>
This is in no way a flame.  It is only to help those that have not yet learned some of the basics in the general population on Dranil.<br>
<br>
Topics will be:<br>
<br>
- Assisting<br>
- Pulling<br>
- raiding<br>
- Argo control <br>
<br>
How do you assist?  Some people take it for granted that everyone knows how to assist.  Well not all do.  I have showed a few people 51+ that were amazed when they learned this.  So hear are the basics.<br>
<br>
Your first option, which I think is the best option, is to make a scials hotkey.  You right click to open the Socials hot key and on the first line you type &quot;/assist &lt;name of puller&gt;&quot;.<br>
<br>
example:  /assist Wingedit<br>
<br>
Don't forget the &quot;/&quot; in &quot;/assist wingedit&quot;.  After the socials hotkey is made you can move it over to you Hotkey box by left clicking and holding it to move it over.<br>
<br>
Another option to assist is to target the person you are assisting and just type &quot;/assist&quot;.  This will target what ever the person you had targeted is targeting.<br>
<br>
It is also a good idea to set auto attacking when assisiting off.  This way you can assist the Main assist to find out what target they are attacking without automatically swinging your weapons.  Type<br>
<br>
/assist off<br>
<br>
If the person you wish to assist is not in your group the best way to target that person is to type &quot;/target &lt;nameofperson&gt;&quot;<br>
<br>
example: /target Wingedit<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Pulling is a breeze right?  You go in wack a mob, and run back to the group.  Sounds very simply.  But a lot is taken for granted.<br>
<br>
As a puller you should never switch targets.  If you wack mob A, when you get back to your party make sure you are attacking Mob A.  Don't ever let it leave your target box.<br>
<br>
If multiply mobs come and Mob B, and Mob C show up to the camp before Mob A as a tank you should always wait for Mob A.<br>
<br>
Why not just attack what shows up?  Because it screws up everyones assisting.  When the Main assist switchs targets after someone has already assisted them it is a nightmare for whomever is doing crowd control.  You have party members attacking different mobs.<br>
<br>
United a group stands, divided they fall easily.  The only time a MA (main assist) should switch mobs is when there is something that cannot be controled by whomever is doing crowd control. ( Enchanter mezzing, Bard mezzing, necro mezzing, or if it's just someone rooting)<br>
<br>
If you are in a group with an enchanter, and they get a mez or 2 resisted and get beat down a little... SO WHAT.  It is the clerics job to heal the enc, and usually gain agro from healing to give the enchanter a breath to mez.  It is also the enchanters job to be prepared for this.  Enchanters should not depend on their channeling skill when getting attacked.  Why do you think they have color stuns.  IF they don't use em, let em die.<br>
<br>
A tank should never consider switching mobs because a caster or cleric is taking damage in a fight when grouped with an enchanter, UNLESS the enchanter says so because the mob is too high to mez.  It is the job of the enchater to mez mobs on clerics and casters first, and the job of the healer to keep the chanter alive and other casters to root mobs if necessary.  Tanks plays no roll in this normally.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Raiding is the most difficult of all.  Having 30+ people all doing their jobs effectly with no one screwing up is a rare thing for the general population on any server.<br>
<br>
If you follow what I said in assisting most of the troublesom areas are covered.  Here are some other basic things to remember.<br>
<br>
Do not Sit Down when a pull is in progress.  Most places like the planes the mobs run right pass the takes to the casters when incoming.  This is especially relvenant in plane of fear.<br>
<br>
Watch for the Incomming messge, stand for about 3-5 seconds while the tanks and enchanters do their jobs then sit.<br>
<br>
Avoid area of effect spells always.  As enchanters I recommend using level 4 and lvl 20 color stuns.  The raduis, mana, and casting time on higher level color stuns ain't worth it anyhow. ( But that's a diff topic)<br>
<br>
If you are a caster and feel the need to BURN on a raid, DO NOT do it from the back of the group.  Go up next to the mob among the tanks so that if you get hit 15+ tanks don't end up looking around for a mob.<br>
<br>
Always give the tagger on a raid ROOM TO TAG.  Don't stand in front of them, or even next to them.  Stay well back until mobs are ready to be engaged.<br>
<br>
The rest is my own personal opinions on how to handle mobs on raids.  I have seen a lot of different methods that I do not agree with personally.  So please read with a grain of salt.<br>
<br>
When mobs are mezzed on a raid I think that all Warriors should be taunting the MA's next mob before breaking mez ( Make sure you have  /assist off set before hitting the assist key) and as soon as the Main Assist breaks the mez all tanks should attack.<br>
<br>
I have noticed on Dranil that on raids the MA is required to acquire taunt then hit a message that says attack now.  This is a load of horseshit in my mind, and dranil is the only place i have ever seen this done.<br>
<br>
Maybe this came about because people were assisting the MA and did not have /assist off set and were breaking the mezzes.   So this waiting period was put in.  Doing it this way is flawed for normal raiding conditions.<br>
<br>
If the Main Assist is the only one taunting on the break of a mez often times it will be the enchanter/shaman/clerics that get the first few wacks.<br>
<br>
All warriors should be taunting, so the mob has a better chance of staying where it is.  Normally the Main Assist is the highest level and has the best gear anyhow, so he will get the agro in the long run.  Situtations like this is not about having 1 person to heal.  There is usually a cleric in every group, and usually all but group 1 never have an issue with mana.  So what if another tank gets hit or tanks a mob entirly for a whole round.  Better him/her then a caster/shaman/cleric, and you see less mobs running all over the place.<br>
<br>
I am getting tired of typing now, this post has already taken me 10 mins  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   So I'll move on to argo control.<br>
<br>
<br>
Argo control is about the hardest for most people to learn imo.  I won't say much on it except the basics.<br>
<br>
If you are in a group with a warrior of equal level and equipment as a ranger/Sk/Pallie/monk...ect.  Let the warrior take the argo.  They have the best AC/HPs.  There is no need for halfbreads to unload mana at the beginning of a fight.<br>
<br>
I am sure some will argo ( well not rangers ) that they can tank as well as a warrior as a pallie/Sk, but really... learn the class's before you get head strong on how well you can tank.<br>
<br>
A CH on a warrior is more mana efficent then on any other class.  Remember the fact that I mentioned people are equally equipped and level wise.<br>
<br>
Monks/rogues/rangers using procing weapons should be taken in the back alley and feed to a dragon.  You are classified as Mana sinks, and any smart cleric should ask you to change weapons.<br>
<br>
Sure Monks have FD, rangers Jolt, and rogues evade.  On a normal mob it's usually not an issue.  When a tuff named pops you 3 classes get your asses handed to you so fast that it can effect the outcome due to the wasted mana used trying to keep you alive.  FD does not always work ( &quot;you have fallen to the ground&quot;) Jolt is iffy at times, and evade is not as effective as it once was.<br>
<br>
Taunt is based on a points system, the person with the most points has the argo.  Evade used to bring a rogues points down to Zero, but has been changed now and only lowers a rogues taunt points for each syccessful attempt.  Jolt works the same way.  FD does not lower your points as far as I know, but gives the MA a few seconds to built more points before you get up. ( not much damage being done on your backside on the floor either)<br>
<br>
So please think about what weapons you are using for grouping and how your taunt points will add up.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
As a caster/Druid learn your spells well.  A druid on snare duty should not snare mobs at the beginning of a fight.  Wait till a mob is 50 percent, or snare mobs that have already been mezzed or are attacking an enchanter that had a mez resisted.  A caster nuking should applie the same rules.  Nuking when a mob is full health should get you a seat in the ally.<br>
<br>
Clerics should stick to celestial healing type spells to keep tanks alive until all mobs are under control.  CHing a tank just making it back from pulling 5-6 mobs and nothing has been mezzed will definatly lighten up your day.<br>
<br>
Enchanters should never make their first spell on a pull a color stun for all the mobs. ( unless the tank is almost dead, then hopefully you have AE mez memmed instead )  Should always target a mob and mez, if resisted move a few feet away from the pack of mobs, Color stun it, and attempt it again.<br>
<br>
I am not gonna run through every class, and sceniro.  I just wanted to state some basic stuff that will keep people alive in normal circumstances.  Methods always change depending on the enviroment you are in.  In no way does this apply for killing all mobs in eq.<br>
<br>
To some thing up...<br>
<br>
-Make an assist key &quot;/assist whoever&quot;<br>
<br>
-Puller never change targets, if you do, tell your group.<br>
<br>
-When raiding, just make sure you have a leader with a clue  :P<br>
<br>
-Argo control is the most important thing you'll ever learn to make eq a more enjoyable game with less stress.  Don't get hit unless you are suppose to.<br>
<br>
I never tryed to degrade any classes here, and if I did I am sorry.  Every class has it's functions when played correctly imo.  If you took the time to read of of this I salut you, may your gaming experiece be a good one.<br>
