<br>
9 times out of 10 when pulling for a group, you won't need to change targets when bringing in multiple mobs.  There are times, however, when you will need to.  This is where experience and knowing the mobs come into play (on deciding which one to kill first).<br>
<br>
In exp camps where it's not always clear that you have a mob incoming (i.e., camp is in a small room with a small field of view), it's useful to have an &quot;incoming&quot; hotkey.  Nothing fancy, just a note to let the group know you have something coming.  I think mine's set up as &quot;/g inc %t&quot;.  <br>
<br>
Between aggroing the mob and pressing the &quot;inc&quot; hotkey, the puller should have enough time to decide which mob he wants the group to kill first.  Usually I'll aggro the mobs, then press inc hotkey when I'm almost to camp, giving the group enough time to stand/pray/prepare/etc, and giving myself enough time to decide on whether or not I made a good choice of my target. <br>
<br>
If for some reason that I switch mobs after hitting &quot;inc&quot;, then I'll hit it again so the group knows to reassist. <br>
<br>
However, it's uncommon to have to change targets after aggroing a mob.  Usually you'll have time to select the target you want before you aggro him and his nearby buddies.<br>
<br>
<br>
Note for SK's:  SK's are by and large the best aggro-gaining and controlling class.  Where a warrior would have to taunt 2-3 times to ensure aggro on a mezzed mob, you need only cast DC and the mob will never look at the enchanter twice.  This saves a lot of time, especially in situations where it's critical to kill mobs as quickly as possible.  Add in a quick taunt before you cast and you can be rest assured that the mob is on you for the duration of the fight.  This can be a double-edged sword, however.  Most SK's don't have the HP/AC of the average warrior, which means it's more efficient to heal the warrior.  Therefore, the problem is how to transfer aggro to him.  The solution is easy...when the warrior has had enough time to taunt 2 or 3 times after you've broken mez, you simply FD, wait ~3 rounds of combat, then get up. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
On a side note, I've found that in lvl 50+ exp groups, lvl 57-60 SK's and Paladins are good as tanks for mobs that hit up to 275 pts of dmg.  Up to this point, clerics worth their salt can keep them healed and still keep up with the mana regen.  Of course, the margin for error becomes smaller and smaller the closer you get to this number.  Basically when you're fighting mobs this tough, you better hope nobody screws up (although this makes the camp entertaining, imo)  I myself am comfortable tanking in exp camps where the mobs hit up to about 240, with occassional higher-level named mobs available that hit a bit harder.  This covers all of the decent high-level exp camps, so there isn't as much of a problem with hybrids being main tanks as there used to be. <br>
